Anonymous Thu 25 Nov 2021 01:13:51 No.43452642 Report

>>43451425
A big problem with modernism and postmodernism is that it ditches skill almost entirely. There are good ideas to be had, and I think the greatest progress made by modernism and postmodernism (frankly, they're practically the same and IMO postmodernism is only its own thing to not seem laughably conservative) is introducing the widespread practice of taking art beyond a mere "spectator sport" and creating works of art that are meant to be experienced, or which are animate. However, the art scene is completely inbred, and for every decent postmodernist work there are 100 (possibly more) which are total garbage, sometimes literally. Examples I've seen include a crudely penned letter complaining about a reduction of subsidies (for which the artist was paid community money, of course), a video of a man throwing books into the air and shooting them with a shotgun (yes, a video, in a museum), and uncountable garbage sculptures. The city where I live sponsored local sculptors for a few years, exhibiting their work in public. Only two results were worthwhile, and consequently picked up by real museums instead of dumped in a landfill. Strangely enough both had anthropomorphic themes.

But it's not uncommon to walk into a museum filled with contemporary art and see maybe only piece that's even worth a damn. Compared to historical art, which is often a random scattershot of simply what's left, and most of it is great. Of course, they are largely defined by skill rather than the incestuous narcissism of "the idea" that rules contemporary art.

>>43452846
Modernism dates back to the Interbellum, and was a self-proclaimed reaction to the senselessness of WWI. Traditionally impressionism is lumped in with modernism, on the insistence of modernists themselves. I consider this to be false, and indicative of the narcissism that is so common in modernism and post-modernism. But it does give a good idea of the jumping off point: The entire crux of impressionism is to create a work that conveys a certain feeling. An impression of the moment, rather than a recreation. One criticism I've seen of Mondriaan is that he started out as an attempted impressionist, sucked at it, and just made up his own, easier style. In fact, it was called De Stijl, which is also the name of an artist who likes drawing characters from Avatar with prolapsed assholes, so that's a fitting legacy. Picasso is much the same, in my opinion. Middling to bad as a traditional artist, then transitioned to a self-invented style that is more forgiving of a lack of skill. Picasso was also a loud communist, even while abstract art was expressly forbidden in the Soviet Union, which gives another hint: Modernism and post-modernism were, and are, highly political. This seems to be a powerful drive in the self-perpetuation of the system.

Purely on the face of it post-modernism is still repeating the old question Dadaism asked, which was entertaining when it was a new point. But we're past "what are art". These are no longer the 1920's. I would very much like to see the self-fellating, and largely political, side left by the wayside and to see the advances taken into a new direction. But shit, I walk past an art school on the regular. It is populated by boring stereotypes. Without a nudge from the outside, I fear the art world will muddle forth on this path.
